{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> νόος</b>, νόου, ὁ, <br /> <i>Attic dialect</i> <i>contraction</i> <u><b>νοῦς</b></u>, <i>genitive</i> νοῦ: [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Homerus Epicus \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>] uses the <i>contraction</i> form once, in <i>nominative</i>, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.240, compare 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Fragmenta” 205 (5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus never)\">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]: Trag. use <i>contraction</i> form, except in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 742 (iambic), 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Philoctetes” 1209 (Lyric poetry)\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]: <i>Aeolic dialect</i> <i>genitive</i> νῶ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 7th-6th c.BC: Alcaeus Lyricus “Supp.” 9.1; _accusative_ νῶν Sapph.[prev. work]25.2; νόον Ead.70 (assuming variant)\">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]: irregular forms are found in “NT” and later writers, <i>genitive</i> νοός [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" NT.Rom.7.23, LXX.4Mac.1.35; _dative_ νοΐ NT.1Cor.1.10, [2nd c.AD: Aristides Rhetor] “Or.” 35(9).26; _nominative_ _plural_ νόες 1st c.AD: Philo Judaeus 1.86, 3rd c.AD: Plotinus Philosophus 6.7.17, 5th-6th c.AD: Damascius Philosophus “de Principiis” 96; _accusative_ _plural_ νόας 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Fragmenta - fragment uncertainFragmenta incerta” 7.27, 4th c.AD: Iamblichus Philosophus “de Mysteriis” 1.15, 5th c.AD: Ammonius Philosophus “in Aristotelis de Interpretatione commentarius - pars” 243.3 (variant), 5th-6th c.AD: Damascius Philosophus “de Principiis” 103: _Attic dialect_ _plural_ νοῖ, _accusative_ νοῦς, _genitive_ νόων [prev. work] 122, _dative_ νοῖς [prev. passage]\">LXX+NT+1st c.AD+</a>], is rare in early writers, as [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Fragmenta” 471, but frequently in later philosophy: \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__1</b></Level3> <b>mind,</b> as employed in perceiving and thinking, <b>sense, wit,</b> οὐ λῆθε Διὸς πυκινὸν ν. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.461; ν. πολυκερδέα 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 13.255; ν. ὁρῇ καὶ ν. ἀκούει, τἄλλα κωφὰ καὶ τυφλά 5th c.BC: Epicharmus Comicus 249, compare 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 371 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; νόῳ <b>prudently,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 6.320 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; παρὲκ νόον <b>senselessly,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 20.133 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; σὺν νόῳ <b>wisely,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 8.86, 138 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ξὺν νῷ with play on ξυνῷ, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.AD(?): Heraclitus 114 (νόῳ codices 5th c.AD: Stobaeus, Joannes); ξὺν νῷ ἑλομένῳ 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 619b; οὐδενὶ ξὺν νῷ [prev. author] “Cri.” 48c; μηδενὶ ξὺν νῷ 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Nubes” 580; τοῦ νοῦ χωρίς 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Tyrannus” 550; τοῦ ν. κενός [prev. author] “OC” 931 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; νόῳ λαβεῖν τι to apprehend it, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 3.51 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; νόῳ σχεῖν, ἔχειν, <b>recall, remember,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 5.92.ή, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 490a; κοινὸς ν. 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Rh.” 1.37 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus, 2nd c.AD: Arrianus Historicus “Epicteti Dissertationes” 3.6.8 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἀγαθὸς ν., σπουδαῖος ν., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Rh.” 2.61, 1.252 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> νοῦν ἔχειν in two senses, <br /><Level4><b>__2.a</b></Level4> to have <b>sense,</b> be <b>sensible,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 553, “El.” 1013, 1465, 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 535, etc.; ὁ νοῦς ὅδ᾽ αὐτὸς ν. ἔχων οὐ τυγχάνει 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Iphigenia Aulidensis” 1139 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; so ν. ὀλίγον κεκτημένος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ecclesiazusae” 747; σμικρὸν νοῦ κεκτῆσθαι 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Leges” 887e; _impersonal_, τὸ γὰρ περισσὰ πράσσειν οὐκ ἔχει ν. οὐδένα 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Antigone” 68, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Timaeus” 68b \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; compare νουνεχόντως. <br /><Level4><b>__2.b</b></Level4> νοῦν or τὸν ν. ἔχειν to have <b>one's mind</b> directed to something, ἄλλοσ᾽ ὄμμα, θητέρᾳ δὲ ν. ἔχειν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Trachiniae” 272, compare 7th-6th c.BC: Sappho Lyrica “Papyrus fragments” in E. Diehl, 25.2; τὸν ν. πρὸς αὑτὸν οὐκ ἔχων, ἐκεῖσε δέ 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Phoenissae” 1418; δεῦρο ν. ἔχε [prev. author] “Or.” 1181; οἴκοι τὸν ν. ἔχειν [prev. author] “Ion” 251 \">Refs 7th c.BC+</a>]; ποῦ τὸν ν. ἔχει; [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ecclesiazusae” 156 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τὸν ν. ἔχειν πρός τινα or τι (like προσέχειν τὸν ν.) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Thucydides Historicus 7.19, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Gorgias” 504d; πρός τινι [prev. author] “Prt.” 324a, etc.; περί τινος [prev. author] “R.” 534b; ἐν πέρδιξιν “Anthologia Graeca” 7.206 (6th c.AD: Damocharis Epigrammaticus): conversely, ἐπὶ νοῦν ἐλθεῖν τινι\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] to <b>occur</b> to one, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis 3.15, 2nd c.AD: Arrianus Historicus “Anabasis” 7.24.3. \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> <b>mind,</b> more widely, as employed in feeling, deciding, etc., <b>heart,</b> χαῖρε νόῳ [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 8.78; κεῦθε νόῳ 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 1.363; [χόλος] οἰδάνει νόον 9.554; ἐνὶ στήθεσσιν ἀτάρβητος ν. ἐστί 3.63 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ν. ἔμπεδος, ἀκήλητος, ἀπηνής,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 11.813, 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 10.329, 18.381 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ν. εὐμενής, ἄγναμπτος, etc., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “P.” 8.18, 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Prometheus Vinctus” 164 (Lyric poetry), etc.; πολλῶν ἀνθρώπων νόον ἔγνω 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 1.3 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἐκ παντὸς νόου with all his <b>heart and soul,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 8.97 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τῷ νῷ.. κἀπὸ τῆς γλώσσης in <b>heart</b> as well as tongue, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 936: frequently in phrase κατὰ νόον\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] according to one's <b>mind,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.117, 7.104; εἰ τάδ᾽ ἔχει κατὰ νοῦν κείνῳ 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Oedipus Coloneus” 1768 (_anapaest meter_); πράξειας κατὰ ν. τὸν ἐμόν [prev. author] “fragment” 469 (_anapaest meter_); κατὰ ν. πράξας 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Equites” 549; χωρεῖ κατὰ ν. [prev. author] “Pax” 940, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Euthyphro” 3e. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__4</b></Level3> <b>mind, resolve, purpose,</b> ἀγαθῷ νόῳ, i.e. kindly, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.60 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; τί σοι ἐν νόῳ ἐστὶ ποιέει; what do you <b>intend</b> to do? [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\"[prev. work] 109 \">Refs</a>]; ἡμῖν ἐν ν. ἐγένετο εἰπεῖν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 9.46 \">Refs</a>]; ἐν ν. ἔχειν with <i>future</i> <i>infinitive</i>, <b>to intend</b>.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 1.10 (variant)\">Refs</a>]: with <i>present</i> <i>infinitive</i>,[<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. work] 27, 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Respublica” 344d \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ποιέειν τι ἐπὶ νόον τινί to put into his <b>mind</b> to do.., [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.27 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἐπὶ νόον τρέπειν τινί.. [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] 3.21; ταύτῃ [ὁ] ν. ἔφερε [prev. author] 9.120. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__5</b></Level3> <b>reason, intellect,</b> νόου φρενί [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 6th c.BC: Xenophanes Poeta Philosophus 25, compare 4th-5th c.BC: Parmenides Poeta Philosophus 16.2, etc.; θεῖος ν. 3rd c.AD: Democritus Epigrammaticus 112, compare [prev. author] cited in 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Anima” 404a28 \">Refs 6th c.BC+</a>]; opposed to δόξα, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Timaeus” 51d, compare 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “de Anima” 428a5. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level4><b>__5.b</b></Level4> “Mind” as the active principle of the Universe, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Anaxagoras Philosophus 12, etc.; Θαλῆς νοῦν τοῦ κόσμου τὸν θεόν “Placita Philosophorum” 1.7.11; ἡ τοῦ κόσμου γένεσις ἐξ ἀνάγκης καὶ νοῦ συστάσεως 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Timaeus” 48a, compare “Sph.” 249a, “Phlb.” 30c, 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Metaphysica” 1072b20, “de An.” 430a17, 4th-3rd c.BC: Zeno Citieus Stoicus 1.28, 3rd c.AD: Plotinus Philosophus 5.1.4. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>act of mind, thought,</b> ἡμῖν δ᾽ οὔ τις τοῦδε νόος καὶ μῆτις ἀμείνων [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 15.509; οὐ γάρ τις νόον ἄλλος ἀμείνονα τοῦδε νοήσει 9.104; οὐ γὰρ δὴ τοῦτον μὲν ἐβούλευσας νόον αὐτή 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.23. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>purpose, design,</b> νόον τελεῖν τινι [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 23.149; σάφα οἶσθ᾽ οἷος ν. Ἀτρεΐωνος 2.192. \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> <b>sense, meaning</b> of a word, etc., οὗτος ὁ νόος τοῦ ῥήματος [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 7.162, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Ranae” 1439, 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 5.83.4, 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Rh.” 1.106 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus, etc.\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ὁ νόος τῆς θυσίης conjecture for νόμος in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.216 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; <b>meaning</b> of a work of art, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 2nd-3rd c.AD: Philostratus Sophista “Vita Apollonii” 4.28; πολὺς ν. ἐν ὀλίγῃ λέξει συνέσταλται 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.510e \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]; πρὸς τὸν αὐτὸν νοῦν to the same <b>effect,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC-1st c.AD: Strabo Geographus 15.3.7 \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]; πρὸς νοῦν οὐδὲν λέγοντες to the <b>point,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st c.BC: Philodemus Gadarensis Epigrammaticus “Mus.” p.96K.; οὐδὲ νοῦν ἔχον \">Refs 1st c.BC+</a>]<b>senseless,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" [prev. author] “Po.” 5.29. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__IV</b></Level2> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Pythagoras Philosophus name for μονάς, “Theologumena Arithmeticae” 6. (Etym. uncertain; the _proper name_ Πολυνόϝα “IG” 9(1).870 hardly proves νόϝος.) \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]","strongNumber":"G3563","accentedUnicode":"νοῦς","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G1097","matchingForm":"γινώσκω","stepTransliteration":"ginōskō","gloss":"to know","_zh_tw_Gloss":"知道","_es_Gloss":"sabe